<h1 id="Search-Algorithms">Navigating Data Structures using Search Algorithms<a class="anchor-link" href="#Search-Algorithms">&#182;</a></h1><h2 id="Part-1---Introduction">Part 1 - Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#Part-1---Introduction">&#182;</a></h2><p>In this tutorial series, we will construct below search algorithms step by step, intuitively and programmatically.</p>
<ol>
<li>Breadth First Search  (BFS)</li>
<li>Depth First Search (DFS)</li>
<li>Uniform Cost Search (UCS)</li>
<li>A Star (A*)</li>
</ol>
<p><em>Prerequisite</em>: Basic Python</p>
<h2 id="Problem-Definition:">Problem Definition:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Problem-Definition:">&#182;</a></h2><p>We will learn by solving a problem. Below is a famous Arad to Bucharest path finding problem used in multiple AI courses across the globe. The lines connecting cities are assumed to be straight routes, cities considered as points, and cost mentioned is just the straight line distance <font color='blue'>(SLD)</font> between the city geo spatial points (latitude, longitude). This is to keep away all complexities to understand the foundations better.  Note, our initial problem is adapted heavily for our tutorial purposes.</p>
<p>The problem statement: <strong><font color='blue'>find a route from Arad to Bucharest</font></strong></p>
<p>Since we will learn the algorithm by programming, we shall create a dictionary explaining only the graph just with geo spatial position (approximately values from internet), and connecting cities. I have created another snippet (abstracted here), which would create a diagram for us from this dictionary to help us visualize as we go forward. Also it calculates and displays the actual "cost" between cities, by calculated the straight line distance between two geo spatial points by <a href="https://geopy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/">geodesic</a> method.</p>

<p>Note that all routes in above map are <strong>open ended</strong>. This setup is purpose fully done. This is now a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(graph_theory%29">tree</a> problem. There are no closed loops. A tree is a type of Graph. A Graph might contain closed loops which we will see shortly.</p>
<p>Below is a sample illustration of how the <strong>SLD</strong> between cities are calculated. There could be any strategy. One could include fuel cost, curved routes cost, etc.</p>

</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">geopy.distance</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">math</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">floor</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">calculate_GD</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">start</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">end</span><span class="p">):</span>

    <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y0</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">start</span>
    <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y1</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">end</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">floor</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">geopy</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">distance</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">geodesic</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">y0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">x0</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">x1</span><span class="p">))</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">miles</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">M</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">romania_location_map_open_full</span>
<span class="n">cost</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">calculate_GD</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">M</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;Arad&#39;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">&#39;pos&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span><span class="n">M</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;Sibiu&#39;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">&#39;pos&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>  <span class="c1">#calculating between Arad and Sibiu</span>
